<subSubSection lastPageId="23" lastPageNumber="56" pageId="22" pageNumber="55" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="22.[151,1436,1913,2010]" lastBlockId="23.[151,1436,151,573]" lastPageId="23" lastPageNumber="56" pageId="22" pageNumber="55">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,335,1948,1973]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="55" reason="1">Comments.</emphasis>
This species was recently described by 
<bibRefCitation author="Almquist, S." box="[806,997,1948,1973]" pageId="22" pageNumber="55" pagination="1 - 284" refId="ref13036" refString="Almquist, S. (2005) Swedish Araneae, part 1, families Atypidae to Hahniidae. Insect Systematics &amp; Evolution, Supplement 62, 1 - 284." type="journal article" year="2005">Almquist (2005)</bibRefCitation>
, where, regrettably, he made a partial confusion with 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Palmgren" authorityYear="1939" box="[325,418,1986,2009]" class="Arachnida" family="Lycosidae" genus="Pardosa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="22" pageNumber="55" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eiseni">
<emphasis box="[325,418,1986,2009]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="55">P. eiseni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. His figs 227a–e is said to illustrate the male and female of 
<emphasis box="[1095,1194,1985,2010]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="55">
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Roberts" authorityYear="1985" box="[1095,1190,1985,2010]" class="Arachnida" family="Lycosidae" genus="Pardosa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="22" pageNumber="55" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="trailli">P. trailli</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
Figs 227a–b shows a palp of 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Roberts" authorityYear="1985" box="[242,336,151,176]" class="Arachnida" family="Lycosidae" genus="Pardosa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="23" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="trailli">
<emphasis box="[242,336,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="56">P. trailli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but it is malformed (notably distal part of cymbium). A drawing of a normal male is therefore given in this paper (
<figureCitation box="[377,461,188,213]" captionStart="FIGURES 17–19" captionStartId="5.[151,264,961,984]" captionTargetBox="[166,1436,206,938]" captionTargetId="figure-380@5.[151,1436,193,940]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 17–19. 17-18, Pardosa fomichevi sp. n.: left male palp (17), epigyne (18). 19, P. trailli: left male palp. Scale lines 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4956526" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4956526/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="56">Fig. 19</figureCitation>
). Fig. 227d in 
<bibRefCitation author="Almquist, S." box="[628,817,188,213]" pageId="23" pageNumber="56" pagination="1 - 284" refId="ref13036" refString="Almquist, S. (2005) Swedish Araneae, part 1, families Atypidae to Hahniidae. Insect Systematics &amp; Evolution, Supplement 62, 1 - 284." type="journal article" year="2005">Almquist (2005)</bibRefCitation>
, however, shows the dorsal (inner) view of an epigyne of 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Palmgren" authorityYear="1939" box="[181,273,224,248]" class="Arachnida" family="Lycosidae" genus="Pardosa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="23" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eiseni">
<emphasis box="[181,273,224,248]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="56">P. eiseni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(in which the horn-like structures containing fertilization ducts are close at midline of epigyne, contrary to the configuration in 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Roberts" authorityYear="1985" box="[407,499,260,285]" class="Arachnida" family="Lycosidae" genus="Pardosa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="23" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="trailli">
<emphasis box="[407,499,260,285]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="56">P. trailli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(cf. Figs 99 &amp; 113).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="23.[151,1436,151,573]" pageId="23" pageNumber="56">
This species is restricted to Britain and Scandinavia (
<figureCitation box="[806,905,295,320]" captionStart="FIGURE 128" captionStartId="22.[151,250,1821,1843]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,195,1799]" captionTargetId="figure-110@22.[151,1436,193,1799]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="FIGURE 128. Distribution of Pardosa eiseni (black circles), P. giebeli (black blobs), P. lasciva (blue crosses), P. nigra (green triangles) and P. trailli (red triangles) in Europe. For open red triangle in the Faroe Islands see text under P. trailli." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4956564" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4956564/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="56">Fig. 128</figureCitation>
). The record from the 
<collectingCountry box="[1164,1315,295,320]" name="Faroe Islands" pageId="23" pageNumber="56">Faroe Islands</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Schenkel, E." pageId="23" pageNumber="56" pagination="395 - 406" refId="ref15332" refString="Schenkel, E. (1925) Fauna Faeroensis. Araneina. Entomologiske Meddelelser, 14, 395 - 406." type="journal article" year="1925">Schenkel 1925</bibRefCitation>
) was given as 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Palmgren" authorityYear="1939" box="[391,488,333,356]" class="Arachnida" family="Lycosidae" genus="Pardosa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="23" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eiseni">
<emphasis box="[391,488,333,356]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="56">P. eiseni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but the accompanying illustration most probably shows a female of 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Roberts" authorityYear="1985" box="[1305,1401,332,357]" class="Arachnida" family="Lycosidae" genus="Pardosa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="23" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="trailli">
<emphasis box="[1305,1401,332,357]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="56">P. trailli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. It remains to be investigated whether the disjunct occurrence in Scandinavia (cf. map in 
<bibRefCitation author="Kronestedt, T." box="[1134,1323,367,392]" pageId="23" pageNumber="56" pagination="281 - 290" refId="ref14176" refString="Kronestedt, T. (2004) Studies on species of Holarctic Pardosa groups (Araneae, Lycosidae). VI. On the identity of Pardosa luciae Tongiorgi with notes on P. trailli (O. P. - Cambridge) and some other species in the P. nigra - group. Denisia, 12, 281 - 290." type="journal article" year="2004">Kronestedt 2004</bibRefCitation>
) is due to lack of collecting activities.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="23.[151,1436,151,573]" pageId="23" pageNumber="56">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,298,439,464]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="56" reason="1">Habitat.</emphasis>
Open stony ground (e.g. scree slopes) in mountains. In Britain, 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Roberts" authorityYear="1985" box="[1012,1103,439,464]" class="Arachnida" family="Lycosidae" genus="Pardosa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="23" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="trailli">
<emphasis box="[1012,1103,439,464]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="56">P. trailli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is recorded from 
<quantity box="[1300,1436,439,464]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.015" metricValueMax="1.3" metricValueMin="0.73" pageId="23" pageNumber="56" unit="m" value="1015.0" valueMax="1300.0" valueMin="730.0">730-1300 m</quantity>
asl. In 
<collectingCountry box="[230,322,476,501]" name="Sweden" pageId="23" pageNumber="56">Sweden</collectingCountry>
, it is found on high mountains close to or above timberline. In 
<collectingCountry box="[1053,1144,476,500]" name="Norway" pageId="23" pageNumber="56">Norway</collectingCountry>
, it is a pioneer species in alpine glacier foreland (
<bibRefCitation author="Braten, A. T. &amp; Flo, D. &amp; Hagvar, S. &amp; Hanssen, O. &amp; Mong, C. E. &amp; Aakra, K." box="[417,623,511,536]" pageId="23" pageNumber="56" pagination="2 - 15" refId="ref13255" refString="Braten, A. T., Flo, D., Hagvar, S., Hanssen, O., Mong, C. E. &amp; Aakra, K. (2012) Primary succession of surface active beetles and spiders in an alpine glacier foreland, central south Norway. Arctic, Antarctic, and Alpine Research, 44 (1), 2 - 15. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1657 / 1938 - 4246 - 44.1.2" type="journal article" year="2012">Bråten et al. 2012</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,1432,548,573]" pageId="23" pageNumber="56" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="23.[151,1436,151,573]" box="[199,1432,548,573]" pageId="23" pageNumber="56">
<emphasis box="[199,471,548,573]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="56" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,548,573]" pageId="23" pageNumber="56">Distribution</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[360,459,548,573]" captionStart="FIGURE 128" captionStartId="22.[151,250,1821,1843]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,195,1799]" captionTargetId="figure-110@22.[151,1436,193,1799]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="FIGURE 128. Distribution of Pardosa eiseni (black circles), P. giebeli (black blobs), P. lasciva (blue crosses), P. nigra (green triangles) and P. trailli (red triangles) in Europe. For open red triangle in the Faroe Islands see text under P. trailli." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4956564" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4956564/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="56">Fig. 128</figureCitation>
).
</emphasis>
This species is known from Britain,? 
<collectingCountry box="[895,1047,548,573]" name="Faroe Islands" pageId="23" pageNumber="56">Faroe Islands</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingCountry box="[1062,1172,548,573]" name="Denmark" pageId="23" pageNumber="56">Denmark</collectingCountry>
), 
<collectingCountry box="[1191,1281,548,572]" name="Norway" pageId="23" pageNumber="56">Norway</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[1336,1428,548,573]" name="Sweden" pageId="23" pageNumber="56">Sweden</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
